articles.author: Michael Martina, Ben Blanchard
articles.description: Taiwan's APEC envoy Morris Chang said on Friday that he had informal interactions with U.S. President Joe Biden and discussions with Secretary of State Antony Blinken at a summit in San Francisco, but none with Chinese President Xi Jinping.
articles.title: Taiwan's APEC envoy chatted with Biden at summit, but not Xi

articles.author: Ben Blanchard
articles.description: A potential joint bid for Taiwan's presidency by the island's two main opposition parties was in disarray on Saturday as they bickered on how to agree on who will run for president with time running out to make a decision.
articles.title: Clock ticking as Taiwan opposition bicker over joint presidency bid

articles.author: David Lawder
articles.description: International Monetary Fund Managing Director Kristalina Georgieva said on Friday this week's meeting between U.S. President Joe Biden and Chinese President Xi Jinping is a badly needed signal that the world needs to cooperate more.
articles.title: Exclusive: IMF chief says Biden-Xi engagement an important signal for world to cooperate

articles.author: Carielle Doe, Alphonso Toweh
articles.description: Liberia President George Weah on Friday conceded election defeat to opposition leader Joseph Boakai after a tight race, ending a presidency marred by graft allegations but helping to ensure a smooth transition of power in the once volatile African nation.
articles.title: Liberia President George Weah concedes election defeat to Joseph Boakai

articles.author: Ann Saphir
articles.description: South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol and Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida pledged cooperation on clean-energy supply chains, quantum computing and other innovative technology during a Silicon Valley roundtable on Friday.
articles.title: Japan's Kishida, S. Korea's Yoon talk tech, cooperation in Silicon Valley

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Australia's government said on Saturday it had expressed serious concerns to China after an "unsafe and unprofessional" interaction between an Australian navy vessel and Chinese warship left Australian military divers injured.
articles.title: Australia criticises China for 'unsafe, unprofessional' naval interaction

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Daisaku Ikeda, who helped spread Buddhist thought around the world through Soka Gakkai - Japan's largest religious organisation and an ally of the government - has died, Japanese media said on Saturday.
articles.title: Japan's Daisaku Ikeda, longtime leader lay Buddhist Soka Gakkai, dies at 95 - media

articles.author: Jeffrey Dastin, Anna Tong, Samrhitha A, Krystal Hu
articles.description: The board of the company behind ChatGPT late on Friday fired OpenAI CEO Sam Altman - to many, the human face of generative AI - sending shock waves across the tech industry.
articles.title: ChatGPT maker OpenAI ousts CEO Sam Altman

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, James Mackenzie
articles.description: Israel issued a fresh warning to Palestinians in the southern city of Khan Younis to relocate west out of the line of fire and closer to humanitarian aid in the latest indication that it plans to attack Hamas in southern Gaza after subduing the north.
articles.title: Israel renews call for Gazans to flee key southern city

articles.author: Joe Skipper, Joey Roulette, Steve Gorman
articles.description: SpaceX's next-generation spacecraft Starship, developed to carry astronauts to the moon and beyond, was set for blastoff on Saturday for a repeat test launch from south Texas, seven months after its first attempt to reach space ended with an explosion.
articles.title: SpaceX Starship set for repeat test flight, seven months after last one blew up
